{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b275ef6a-429b-457b-bed7-38825760c5bb","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the simplest option for .NET apps. For CPU profiling specifically:\n\n```powershell\n# Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU sampling trace (30 seconds example)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n**Alternative — PerfView** (deeper OS-level insight):\n\n```powershell\n# Download PerfView.exe from GitHub, then:\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500 -ThreadTime\n```\n\nPerfView uses ETW and gives you flame graphs, thread-time analysis, and kernel-level CPU stacks.\n\n**Quick guidance:**\n\n| Tool | Best for |\n|------|----------|\n| `dotnet-trace` | Quick managed-code CPU sampling |\n| PerfView | Deep analysis incl. native/kernel frames, blocking, GC |\n| `dotnet-counters` | Live triage (confirm it's actually CPU, not threadpool starvation) |\n\n**Tip:** Before tracing, run `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` to confirm `cpu-usage` is high and check if GC or threadpool contention is the real culprit.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2b2f4c90-5851-4f00-ba2e-457aaf1c1e4a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question - I can answer this from knowledge without needing to look at any files.","outputTokens":416,"requestId":"C3CE:133E03:1B9BF59:1F37FDF:6A07C22D"},"id":"2fa69949-e7a4-434b-89ef-ba361f909e51","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:02:48.835Z","parentId":"6b79108c-e212-4808-9a4f-5b9e53588fd8"}
